sample.title: Donald Trump‚Äôs claims about Nato troops in Afghanistan criticised | BBC News
sample.description:
Donald Trump's claim that Nato troops stayed "a little off the front lines" during the war in Afghanistan has sparked outrage from UK politicians and veterans' families.
 
The US president told Fox News on Thursday that he was "not sure" the military alliance would be there for the US "if we ever needed them".
 
"They'll say they sent some troops to Afghanistan," he said, "and they did, they stayed a little back, a little off the front lines".
 
Health and Social Care Minister Stephen Kinnock called Trump‚Äôs remark ‚Äúdisappointing‚Äù, and said the UK and other allies had "always stood shoulder to shoulder with the United States" and contributed to US-led missions.
 
The UK was among several allies to join the US in Afghanistan from 2001, after it invoked Nato's collective security clause following the 9/11 terror attacks.
 
A total of 457 British service personnel were killed in the conflict.

sample.title: 'I gave my last 46p': Young people say they felt pressured by church to donate | BBC News
sample.description:
The website of the London ICC describes it as being part of a global movement of more than 130 churches worldwide.
 
It claims to be "not your average church", and its student-focused Instagram features slickly edited testimonies from young faces, along with vlogs and vox-pop interviews near university campuses.
 
People we have spoken to, who were all students when they became involved with the ICC, have raised allegations with the BBC about feeling pressured into making donations they could not afford.
 
The London International Christian Church told the BBC the allegation that undue pressure was put on the students for donations was untrue.
 
It said its doctrine was that giving must be "voluntary, in keeping with one's means and never coerced or demanded".
 
Reporter: Jonelle Awomoyi
Producers: John Johnson, James Bryant
Graphics: Manuella Bonomi
